Veeva Systems Inc (VEEV.N) Price Target
Unchanged Impact to our thesis
Modest upside Financial results versus consensus
Modest revision higher Direction of next 12- month consensus EPS
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research

Following strong outperformance since the last earnings report, the bar was arguably higher and billings performance may underwhelm. Management struck a positive tone on the recent agreement with IQVIA regarding longer term implications for revenue and network effect.

Next up is Veeva's annual investor day on October 16, which is earlier than prior years during November and interestingly takes place during Salesforce's annual Dreamforce conference this year. Management commented that it has two new verbal commits to Vault CRM from top 20 pharma companies and that Salesforce (covered by Keith Weiss) has added a new top 20 verbal commit as well.

Veeva beat revenue and EPS in Q2 and guided above for Q3... Revenue increased \(17\%\) y/y to \(\) 789m\(, or 2.7\%\) ahead of the Street (Exhibit 3). The company noted Crossix remained an important source of strength in the quarter, albeit not as strong as the seasonally stronger Q1. Non- GAAP operating income and EPS of \(\) 353m\(and\) \ \(1.99\) came in \(5\%\) ahead. GM of \(77.5\%\) missed the Street by 60 bps, which was attributed to timing of expenses. The company guided Q3 to \(\) 791.5m\(in revenue, non - GAAP operating income of\) \ \(349m\) and EPS of \(\) 1.94\(, around 1.5\%\) ahead of the Street. Veeva increased cash flow guidance by \(\) 120m\(, driven by a\) \ \(135m\) positive impact from tax legislation under the OBBBA.

...In contrast to in- line billings. Normalized billings increased \(\sim 10\%\) y/y \(\) 666m\(in Q2, in line with the Street. This compares unfavorably to beats of 2\%- 6\%\) over the past 4 quarters and a median of more than 2% since 2021 (Exhibit 1). Veeva guided to billings of \(\) 527m\(in Q3, also in line. The company raised FY26 billings by\) \ \(35m\) or \(\sim 1\%\) , leaving implied Q4 billings of \(\) 1.4bn\(, or 3\%\) ahead of the Street. Of note, Q4 billings represents 43.2% of total FY26 guidance, up from a range of 40.5\%- 42\% in recent years (Exhibit 2). While management spoke confidently on visibility into 2H, a higher implied Q4 could give investors pause considering lingering macro uncertainty across pharma.

Management highlighted new opportunities in AI while noting limited financial impact through 2027. CEO Peter Gassner commented that Veeva will ultimately help create billions of dollars of value for the Life Sciences industry deploying AI but it will take time. Veeva sees the opportunity to reduce hundreds of millions in outsourced labor utilized in clinical trials. In Commercial, the goal is to enhance productivity as opposed to reduce headcount, although that remains a key debate among investors.
Exhibit 1: Billings were in line in Q2, ending the recent streak of upside surprises
Source: Morgan Stanley Research, FactSet, Visible Alpha
Exhibit 2: Implied FQ4 billings is slightly more back- end weighted than recent years
Source: Morgan Stanley Research, Company Filings
Underweight on competitive risks to the business and slowing growth

Veeva provides SaaS solutions for the Life Sciences industry, targeting \(\) 20B\(TAM. Our checks suggest risks to the company's core CRM business (\) \sim 50\% \(of subscription revenue), with Veeva's decision to move off of Salesforce leading customers to reevaluate their CRM. With Veeva already having high market share of\) 80\% \(we estimate that every\) 10\% \(share loss and\) 10\% \(reduction in pricing leads to\) \sim \ \(120mn\) in revenue loss, or a \(5\%\) hit. Given this risk and pressures more broadly on the Life Sciences industry we view the company's 2030 target of\) \ \(6bn\) in sales as ambitious
Source: Refinitiv, Morgan Stanley Research
Contrarian: Negative Disruption: Positive Technology Diffusion: Positive

All figures are approximate risk- neutral probabilities of the stock reaching beyond the scenario price in either three- months' or one- years' time. View explanation of Options Probabilities methodology here

Veeva fends off competition in Commercial CRM and new growth initiatives in R&D lead to growth ahead of our base case CAGR of \(15\%\) in that segment. We model a bull case FCF CAGR of \(24\%\) and apply a \(29x\) EV/FCF multiple, toward the high end of the recent range.

We value VEEV at 19x EV/FCF on 2026. Our \(\) 210\(base case reflects a next twelve months multiple of\) \sim 22x\(, toward the low end of recent years (20x - 30x) to reflect lingering risks to demand in Life Sciences and competitive risks we see to its core CRM business (25 - 30% of revenue). Tighter open controls favorably impact operating margin, which we estimate at\) 43\% \(in CY26.

Growth in the commercial business decelerates further and new growth initiatives in R&D disappoint. Bear case FCF CAGR of \(14\%\) and potential competitive threats from companies like Salesforce leads to a sharper contraction in the multiple to 16x EV/FCF.
